          "text": "I've read all three documents. Here's my understanding:\n\n## v3.0.0 — The Baseline\n\nThe core standard for tracking AI-generated code via Git Notes under `refs/notes/ai`. Each authorship log has two sections:\n\n1. **Attestation Section** — maps file paths to session hashes + line ranges (which lines each AI session wrote)\n2. **Metadata Section** — JSON with `schema_version`, `base_commit_sha`, and a `prompts` map keyed by session hash (SHA-256 of `{tool}:{conversation_id}`, first 16 hex chars)\n\nEach prompt record carries: `agent_id`, `messages` transcript (user/assistant/tool_use, no tool responses), and stats (`total_additions`, `total_deletions`, `accepted_lines`, `overriden_lines`).\n\nSection 2 covers history rewriting (rebase, merge, reset, cherry-pick, stash, amend) — the key principle is that authorship follows content through SHA changes, with \"working state\" migration for uncommitted operations.\n\n## v4.0.0 — Research Extension\n\nBuilds on v3 with six additions:\n\n1. **`change_history`** — chronological array of every checkpoint (human + AI) between parent and current commit, with per-file `added_lines`/`deleted_lines` in compact range format, optional line contents, and `CheckpointLineStats` (including SLOC)\n2. **Human change tracking** — checkpoints no longer skip human-only edits; `humans` map with `h_`-prefixed hashes in attestation\n3. **Context conversations** — zero-code-change prompt records (planning/Q&A) included in `prompts`\n4. **`line-history` command** — traces a line backward through `change_history` using diff reconstruction (`map_new_to_old`, `reverse_through_insert`, etc.)\n5. **Subagent tracking** — `subagents` array on prompt records linking parent to spawned conversations\n6. **Message IDs** — `id` field on messages for finer prompt-to-code traceability; `prompt_id` on change history entries cross-references these\n\nVersion check loosened: v4 accepts any `\"authorship/...\"` prefix. New fields use skip-se